
[1]rupture

   RUP'TURE, n. [L. ruptus, rumpo, to break.]

   1. The act of breaking or bursting; the state of being broken or
   violently parted; as the rupture of the skin; the rupture of a vessel
   or fiber.

   2. Hernia; a preternatural protrusion of the contents of the abdomen.

   3. Breach of peace or concord, either between individuals or nations;
   between nations, open hostility or war. We say, the parties or nations
   have come to an open rupture.

   He knew that policy would disincline Napoleon from a rupture with his
   family.

   RUP'TURE, v.t. To break; to burst; to part by violence; as, to rupture
                               a blood vessel.

              RUP'TURE, v.i. To suffer a breach of disruption.
